# Testing Conventions

## Pick the right level

| What you are testing | Level | Tooling |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Domain / application logic | Plain unit test | JUnit 5 + AssertJ, `InMemoryProductRepository` |
| Controller, DTOs, error contract | REST slice | `@WebMvcTest` + MockMvc + `@MockitoBean` |
| Mongo mapping and repository | Integration | `@DataMongoTest` + Testcontainers |
| Full HTTP flow | E2E (`e2e` package) | `@SpringBootTest` + Rest Assured + Testcontainers |
| Layer dependencies | Architecture | ArchUnit in `architecture` package |

## Style

- Test names state behavior: `shouldRejectNegativeCriterionWeight`, `shouldRankProductsByWeightedScore`. No `test` prefix.
- AssertJ only (`assertThat`, `assertThatThrownBy`); never JUnit assertions or Hamcrest.
- One logical assertion block per test; separate arrange/act/assert with blank lines.
- Assert exact exception messages, since they are part of the API contract:

```java
assertThatThrownBy(() -> new CriterionWeight(-1))
    .isInstanceOf(IllegalArgumentException.class)
    .hasMessage("Criterion weight cannot be negative");
```

## Test data

- Build fixtures with test mothers (`ProductTestMother`, `RankingWeightsTestMother`): `final` class, private constructor, static factory methods named for intent (`productWithSalesUnits(100)`). Extend the mother instead of inlining constructors in tests.
- Tests NEVER rely on the Mongo seed data; each integration/E2E test inserts its own documents and cleans up.

Run with `./mvnw test` (Docker required for Testcontainers).
